And I dunno what the purpose of this thread is really—it’s just been on my mind. But what I do know is that I want to keep writing even more so than before
I used to sometimes wonder where my natural inclination to writing came from since it was clear it didn’t come from my parents but in that moment I knew exactly where.

In a random bin of old tax papers and receipts I found a singular, loose leaf journal entry and almost cried. For one, reading it made me feel close to her. Secondly, I never knew and she never told me how beautifully she could write
On Sunday we finally went to her house to go through her things. She was a hoarder long before I was born so needless to say there was *a lot* to go through and things could be easily missed

In March, my grandma passed away. I won’t go into too much otherwise I’ll start crying but she helped raise me and my sister. She encouraged me to read books, always sat with me as I read aloud to her and was my first supporter when I started writing my own stories as a child

And yet it's nothing compared to the beauty of the smile he pins Hoseok with.

"What else you got?" Yoongi asks.

Yoongi looks up, leans forwards as he places his chin in the palm of his hand, elbow on the glass top of the iron table and head tilted ever so slightly. The sun makes his skin glow and the light in his eyes shimmer.
"Alive, huh," Yoongi murmurs, "That's worth a lot. Many would spend their entire lifetime searching for that kind of feeling."

Yoongi meets Namjoon's smug little smile over the top of his coffee. He drinks slowly; carefully and deliberately. He sets the ceramic mug down onto the saucer hand painted with delicate little details in gold.

"Maybe because he'll make you feel alive," Namjoon chimes in.

In that moment Hoseok has never been more grateful for his friend.

"And why would I marry you?" Yoongi asks as he picks up his coffee to take a sip.

Disbelief.

But Hoseok knows without a shadow of a doubt that they're meant to be together. He can feel it etched right into the bone as if it had been ingrained there.
The words fail him—how is he to know how to translate such an innate and instinctual feeling into simple words that could never measure up to the depth of the way he feels?

He feels the red in his cheeks as he stutters, trying and failing to find the words to explain how he knew with every fiber of his being from the moment he laid eyes on Yoongi that they are meant to be together.
"As my future husband?" Yoongi asks, an edge of playfulness to his tone and yet Hoseok still feels his body turn hot.

"I know," Hoseok says and immediately Yoongi's eyebrow raises.

Hoseok flushes with embarrassment, "I mean—I saw you move in that first week, I've been meaning to introduce myself."
Leaning back in his chair, one arm draped across the back of it, recognition crosses over Yoongi's face, "Ah, I thought you looked familiar. I just opened the tattoo shop next door."
"Oh! No! No, my name's Hoseok, I own the flower shop across the street and the apartment above. We're neighbors. Sort of," Hoseok rambles in explanation.

Min Yoongi.

"Your name is like a melody."

"A singer, huh," Yoongi smirks, the corners of his mouth ticked upwards, his eyes catlike and full of amusement and curiosity, "Is that what you are?"

Namjoon sighs, "Yes, he is."

The boy nods slowly, his eyes now on Hoseok once more, eyeing him carefully.

"I'm Min Yoongi."

Hoseok's smile shines brighter than the sun.

The man is so thrown off by Hoseok's proposal that his friend's, Namjoon's, sudden appearance does little to surprise him.

"Namjoon--is he always like this?" The boy asks and it's then that Hoseok feels the smallest sliver of embarrassment for being so upfront and blunt.

The boy blinks, eyes wide in near disbelief.

"I'm Jung Hoseok," he continues.

The boy glances over Hoseok's shoulder to look at Namjoon who's shaking his head in a mix part of exasperation and fondness as he catches up to them.

The man looks astounded and confused.

"Wha--who are you?" He furrows his eyebrows at Hoseok, bewildered.

Without missing a beat Hoseok says, "The man who's going to marry you."

Before Hoseok even realizes it, he's standing next to the table the man and his friend are sat at, the two deep in conversation. It's only when he speaks that Hoseok's presence is finally noticed.

"Come home with me."

He faces the bakery. Does he start with his name?

One foot in front the other.

Does he ask the man for his name?

Step after step.

Or does he begin with a simple hello?

He nods, unable to speak, as if he'd even be able to hear himself over the roar of his own racing heartbeat and rush of blood. His mind is running a thousand miles a minute, thinking of all that he wants to say, of all that he can say to that beautiful boy.

Hoseok turns his head, reluctantly breaking his gaze away.

"Just... don't come on too strong, alright?"

Hoseok can feel the rise of a flush in his cheeks.
"Hoseok," he hears Namjoon say before clapping a hand on his shoulder once they've reached the other side, nothing but a mere few meters away from Hoseok's future husband.
One step forward and then another—no one else in the world matters or exists to him, even as he has to slip between them all on the crosswalk.
Wide-eyed and nervous, Hoseok swallows thickly. His eyes are set forward, locked onto the boy across the street that he knows without a shadow of a doubt that he will love.

Hoseok nods again, entranced and fixated, without a second glance to Namjoon.

Namjoon nudges Hoseok's side, ushering him forward with a prod and a sly smile, "Come on. Let's go over and maybe you can actually talk to him instead of staring at him like a creep."

Hoseok can't take his gaze off the boy even as he nods, barely registering his friend's question.

"Yes," he breathes.

Namjoon chuckles, exasperated and fond and amused.

"Do you want to talk to him? I can introduce you."
"Wait—is he the guy you told me you were going to marry even though you haven't met?" Namjoon asks, the corner of his lips quirked up into a smile.
A moment and one more passes and yet Hoseok can't stop staring at the man across the street, smiling and laughing with his friend. Hoseok's chest swoops with the curve of his smile.

Namjoon squints his eyes as if it'll make him see clearer.

"I'm pretty sure that's him—we're old friends," Namjoon says, "He told me that he was opening a shop downtown but I didn't know it'd be across the street from yours. Small world, huh?"

The name snaps Hoseok out of his reverie. The people around him begin to move in regular motion, no longer slowed by the heavy gaze in which the man pinned him with.

"Yoongi-hyung?"

Namjoon follows Hoseok's gaze as he's still yet to tear his eyes away from the man across the street.

"Is that Yoongi-hyung?"

He smiled.

Did he know? Did he know just like Hoseok did?

"Oi," Namjoon says, sending Hoseok hurtling back down to Earth, "What're you looking at?"

And then the man turns his gaze back to that faceless friend of his as he joins the other outside, his expression easy and relaxed.

The two find a table in the small outdoor seating area of the bakery, still in view of Hoseok's florist shop.
It's only a moment, over the unknowing crowd that passes by them in a blur of slow motion, a brief meeting of eyes. Despite how long Hoseok lives in that moment, it lasts but a second or two.

He lets the door fall shut behind himself, and as it does he looks up as though he can feel himself being watched.

His eyes meet Hoseok's. He smiles—soft and but a small upturn yet full of warmth all the same.

Through what little he can make out through the window, Hoseok watches the two order at the counter before they head back outside with their drinks. The tattoo shop owner, the love of Hoseok's life, is the first to step out into the pleasant springtime.

Hoseok watches as the man he's to marry leaves the tattoo shop with another, the younger one that helped set up the shop and seems to work there as well. They don't go far, just past the bookstore into the bakery next door to it.
Movement across the street catches Hoseok's eye and draws his attention like a magnet, Namjoon's voice slowly fades away into a low mumble.
Namjoon's eye momentarily widen before his expression softens into one of understanding, "I hadn't thought of it like that before but it makes sense."

"There's more to flowers than just colors and shapes," Hoseok says, "If you pick the right ones and combine them in a garden or bouquet together, you begin to see them for what they are and how beautiful they truly can be."
Hoseok hums in agreement. It may be an odd combination to some but Hoseok has always loved the contrast of the simple and delicate flowers paired with the ever eccentric and eye-catching sunflowers.

Once Namjoon steps away from the barrel planter Hoseok turns his water hose to the delphiniums and daisies in the barrel planter.

"Seeing them together now, they pair quite nicely," Namjoon comments.

Namjoon likes to spend his Tuesday afternoons helping Hoseok in the shop and today is no different. He carries a barrel, cut in half and repurposed into a planter, from inside so Hoseok can water it and push it next to the door for display underneath the boxes on the window.

It's warm out but pleasant, and Hoseok is over the moon because the sunflowers are reaching with all their might up towards the sky. With just the right angle the spray of the water casts a small rainbow.

Namjoon is with him the next time it happens.

Once again Hoseok is out on the sidewalk, watering the flower boxes under the window front of his shop.

He waved back.

Hoseok beams and steps away from the window feeling more hopeful. Maybe he doesn't need words but there is one thing Hoseok is absolutely sure of: he is going to marry that man.

Hoseok lifts a hand and waves, a little more sure of himself than he actually feels. A pause.

And then the man waves back, more shyly than Hoseok had, before his attention returns to the notebook in his lap.

His eyes are dark and deep, they bore directly into Hoseok's despite the space between them. In that simple moment Hoseok feels like his entire being has been stripped raw and understood. He feels exposed but he isn't afraid of it.

As though he can feel himself being watched, the man looks up and meets Hoseok's gaze from across the way. People pass below them, blurs moving in slow motion as the world turns, the rain continues to pour and Hoseok is frozen in place at his neighbor having finally looked at him
Hoseok's mind wanders so much that he forgets himself and that he's standing in his own window, mug of tea cupped with both hands as he stares through the streaks of water.

Hoseok wonders what he's completely absorbed in, if the moody weather prompted him to open his curtains for the first time. Did he enjoy the rain? Did it inspire him or was it the sound against the glass window panes that put him at ease?

From what Hoseok can see his neighbor is sitting by the window in a large armchair, either writing or drawing. There's too much space between them to be able to tell but Hoseok can see him holding a notebook with his hand moving across the page.
There is a moment, shortly after the tattoo shop finally opened, on a rainy Sunday afternoon where Hoseok catches a glimpse of his neighbor with the curtains in his apartment drawn.
So he has made himself content to long from afar.

Weeks pass and Hoseok does nothing more than adore from afar as the man settles into this new life of his. Every time he thinks of popping in to introduce himself it's as though he has forgotten every language that has existed. What is he supposed to say when he has no words?

Over the course of a week Hoseok quickly realizes that his new neighbor is opening a tattoo studio. Normally there are a couple others helping him, a man and a woman covered in ink that Hoseok presumes must be the other artists at the shop.

Hoseok wants to introduce himself but he can't find the right time. His new neighbor is constantly busy between unpacking his things while playing beautiful songs from a speaker that drift out onto the street and setting up the shop below into the late hours of the night.

Hoseok has never been more grateful to live in the apartment above his shop. Everyday he catches quick glimpses, a few moments to watch his new neighbor move and settle in not only into the apartment but also the shop beneath.
He stands there and watches Yoongi carry box after box up the metal stairs.

Blurred versions of people cross over his vision but Hoseok doesn't see any of them. He doesn't hear a word any of them say when they have to sidestep around him, it's all a distant jumble of words under the muffled mumble of the city and Hoseok's own racing heart.
There are countless people on the street passing by Hoseok, stood frozen on the sidewalk in front of the flower boxes outside his shop, watering can in his hand forgotten.

Hoseok knows it, with every fiber of his being, from the moment his eyes fall on Yoongi from across the street where Yoongi moves into the small apartment above the empty storefront available for lease.

The person that Hoseok wants to go to bed with every night and wake to in the mornings, when sleep still has a heavy hold over them and they navigate to one another across the bed sheets until they find the warmth and comfort in each other's arms during those early morning hours.
Hoseok knows from that very moment that Yoongi is the person Hoseok wants to know inside and out, the person Hoseok wants to know *him* inside and out.
Hoseok knows from the first moment he lays eyes on Yoongi that he's going to marry him.

He shoved the image of the person out of his mind or at least did his best to. Still, Yoongi pedaled faster.

Yoongi pushed forward and took off down the dirt road once more, pedaling faster than he had been before. He wasn’t scared, there was nothing to be scared of. He just wanted to get the delivery over with. That’s all.

He wasn’t sure what the answer was, or if he even wanted to know, so Yoongi blinked a few times and steeled himself. His nerves were getting to him. That’s what it had to be.

You’ll catch your death out there.

Where could they have gone so quickly? Were they hiding behind a tree, waiting for him to pass? Had it been his imagination?

Nothing good comes out of the marshes.

It was a fleeting moment that felt like eternity, yet the moment blinked, Yoongi shook his head to do a double take--the figure was gone.

Yoongi skidded to a halt and whipped his head around, looking for the person out in the marshes.

Their eerie stance, hands by their side, stark still aside from their eyes following Yoongi, sent a chill down his spine. When their eyes met Yoongi was startled to see one was a startling white, the other so deep and dark it looked as black as night.

Standing in waist deep water was a person, skin tan and hair long, near white and curled. From afar Yoongi couldn’t tell who they were, their long gown dirtied and stained as it hung loosely from their frame. They stood facing Yoongi, watching him.

Around another bend and a glimpse of white caught Yoongi’s attention, stark against green and browns of the marshes. He looked over his shoulder and off in the distance, out in the murky water he saw it and his heart skidded to a halt.

The path curved around a bend of trees and Yoongi leaned towards the side just slightly so he wouldn’t have to slow down. Just after that curve came another, the dirt road snaked through the marshlands with endless curves and twists.

Myung-Dae said the trip wouldn’t be too long, it was only half a mile past the iron gate. Yoongi would reach his destination soon and then he’d be back on his way to the shop. At least that’s what he told himself.
There was nothing but marshland and spanish moss hanging from the limbs of trees. His nerves were beginning to calm. He was fine, there was nothing to worry about.
The dirt road through the marshes was long and winding, Yoongi couldn’t even guess the end of it through the thick of trees. As he pedaled along, Yoongi looked from side to side.

Even the creepy, one eyed crow from before had taken off. Yoongi reassured himself that he was fine; if Myung-Dae could make weekly deliveries with no issue, then there was nothing to worry about. 

Not even gators.

and the dirt road hardly seemed like it’d been given much upkeep since the day it was made from all the potholes and dips.

A smug smirk ticked up the edges of Namjoon’s lips. The fire crackled and popped.

“That depends on who you ask.”

Beside him the dark haired camper looked at Namjoon with mild interest, if only for a moment, before his gaze turned forward again and he kept his eyes trained on the fire. But it was apparent that he was listening just as intently as the blonde he traveled with.
“Curse? Why did the witch curse them?” the blonde asked, head cocked to the side.

“No one cares about that,” Seokjin heckled while Jungkook chimed in; “You forgot to tell them that half the town is gone because of the witch’s curse.”

Namjoon looked at them with only mild annoyance, like one would a younger sibling, “I didn’t forget, I was getting to that.”

“It’s a local story from a small town further south, not too far from us actually. It still exists on maps but it’s near empty these days,” Namjoon started, “Most the people that live there now are only there because their ancestors lived there before, it’s a familial thing.”
Namjoon knew it better than them all, always told it with more care to detail and a tone that always sent a chill down their spines even though they all knew the story well enough.

“Alright, alright, I will,” Namjoon waved him off and turned to the three newcomers.

Meanwhile, Hoseok groaned with reluctance as the other two scooted closer around the fire, eager to hear the story despite having heard it many times before.

Seokjin snorted, “Nah, I just said all that to get under Joonie’s skin, it’s fun.”

Jungkook’s nose scrunched up with his laugh while Namjoon looked partially annoyed but mostly displeased at Seokjin’s comment.

“Go on,” Seokjin encouraged, “tell them about it.”

Seokjin barked with laughter, his head thrown back from the force of the laugh rippling through his chest “Oh! Now you have to tell them.”

“I thought you didn’t think it was real so why are you so eager for Namjoon to tell them about it?” Jungkook narrowed his eyes at Seokjin.

Hoseok shuddered. “Can we not do this out here?”

Jungkook leaned over and bumped his shoulder playfully against Hoseok’s, “What, you scared?”

“It’s just a story about a witch, what’s there to be afraid of?” asked the blonde.

The blonde leaned in closer to Namjoon, intrigued, his eyes big with curiosity.

“Not really, no,” spoke up one of them with dark hair and cheeks like dumplings.

“Go on Namjoon, tell them about the green witch,” Seokjin encouraged with a swig from his beer.

“You two must not be from around here if you’re asking that,” said Jungkook.

The pair behind the blonde shared a quick side glance to one another. Even with the glow of firelight their looks went unnoticed by the other campers.

The blonde newcomer cocked his head to the side, even his two companions seemed interested in the tale that Namjoon had mentioned.

“The green witch?” He questioned, “What’s that?”
“You know you’re not even supposed to talk about it--that’s how you summon it,” Hoseok chastised and knocked Namjoon’s shoulder as if it could knock some sense into him.

“Oh, are they now?” Seokjin cut him off, antagonizing Namjoon further.

“Must you two argue about this everytime the green witch is mentioned?” Jungkook groaned.
Namjoon shook his head, “Look, just because you don’t believe it doesn’t mean it never happened. You can look at the records--the number of people that died from the green witch are documented--”
“Oh, right, right,” Seokjin agreed sarcastically. “And I suppose he also knew the mothman and goatman too, right?”
“No,” Namjoon protested and shot Seokjin a look, “I say that because my great-grandfather used to live in the town when everything happened, he experienced everything for himself.”
“You’re only saying that because your grandfather told you the story and you used to believe anything he says,” Seokjin said.

He was given but a collection of eye rolls from Jungkook and Seokjin, sat next to him, while Hoseok leaned in closer. Under his breath Jungkook muttered that the goatman was indeed real while the mothman wasn’t, but the comment went ignored by all, if not entirely missed.
“Because unlike the mothman or goatman, the green witch was actually real,” Namjoon said with a shrug, as if it was obvious.

Namjoon turned his attention to his bickering friends, “While mothman and goatman are equally scary in their own right, we all know the green witch is the most terrifying.”
Jungkook scoffed, “Yeah? And why’s that?”
“There’s nothing to be afraid of, Hoseokie,” Seokjin assured him with a wave of his hand, fingers still wrapped around the neck of the beer bottle, but it did little to quell Hoseok’s nerves.
“Do we have to talk about cryptids right now? While it’s dark out?” Cut in Hoseok, eyes as big as a doe’s and heart shaped lips turned down into a frown with his furrowed brows.

However he didn’t even have a chance to protest before Seokjin loudly exclaimed.

“He’s a giant moth! There’s nothing about that more terrifying than the goatman!”

“Oh, don’t worry,” replied a small blonde, “I’m used to petty arguments thanks to this one.”
He jerked his head to the side, motioning to the man that sat next to him who gave an indignant look of his own; rather scandalized before he narrowed his eyes.

The others around the campfire watched the pair with amusement as they continued to argue. 

“Please ignore them,” Namjoon said to the two newcomers in the group, “They get into petty arguments like this all the time.”

Seokjin rolled his eyes while he handed Jungkook the second beer, “Mothman is much more iconic.”

“But goatman is more plausible! Think about it,” Jungkook protested, “are you really going to sit there and tell me that I’m wrong?”
“Are you trying to tell me that mothman is real but goatman isn’t?” Asked Jungkook, his two front teeth reminiscent of a bunny and round cheeks that gave away his youth despite his toned build.
